root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2007</fr:anchor><fr:addr>hodge-theory-iii-introduction</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-introduction.xml</fr:route><fr:title>Introduction</fr:title><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>
  This article follows <fr:link
href="hodge-theory-i.xml"
type="local"
addr="hodge-theory-i">Hodge Theory I</fr:link> and <fr:link
href="hodge-theory-ii.xml"
type="local"
addr="hodge-theory-ii">Hodge Theory II</fr:link>;
  the numbering of the sections here follows that of <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii"
href="hodge-theory-ii.xml"
taxon="Hodge Theory"
number="II"></fr:ref> (which contains <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-1"
href="hodge-theory-ii-1.xml"
number="1"></fr:ref> to <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-4"
href="hodge-theory-ii-4.xml"
number="4"></fr:ref>).
</fr:p><fr:p>
  In <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii"
href="hodge-theory-ii.xml"
taxon="Hodge Theory"
number="II"></fr:ref>, we gave an introduction to the yoga that underlies <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii"
href="hodge-theory-ii.xml"
taxon="Hodge Theory"
number="II"></fr:ref> and the present article <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-iii"
href="hodge-theory-iii.xml"
taxon="Hodge Theory"
number="III"></fr:ref>.
  However, <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii"
href="hodge-theory-ii.xml"
taxon="Hodge Theory"
number="II"></fr:ref> and <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-iii"
href="hodge-theory-iii.xml"
taxon="Hodge Theory"
number="III"></fr:ref> are logically independent of <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-i"
href="hodge-theory-i.xml"
taxon="Hodge Theory"
number="I"></fr:ref>;
  they also do not contain all the results that were stated in <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-i"
href="hodge-theory-i.xml"
taxon="Hodge Theory"
number="I"></fr:ref>.
</fr:p><fr:p>
  In <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii"
href="hodge-theory-ii.xml"
taxon="Hodge Theory"
number="II"></fr:ref>, we introduced the Hodge theory of non-singular (not necessarily complete) algebraic varieties.
  Here we treat the case of arbitrary singularities.
  From [hodge-theory-iii-7 <fr:strong>(?)</fr:strong>] onwards, we will make essential use of results from <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-1"
href="hodge-theory-ii-1.xml"
number="1"></fr:ref> to <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-3"
href="hodge-theory-ii-3.xml"
number="3"></fr:ref>.
</fr:p><fr:p>
  In the case of a <fr:em>complete</fr:em> singular algebraic variety <fr:tex>X</fr:tex>, the fundamental idea is to use the resolution of singularities to replace <fr:tex>X</fr:tex> by a simplicial system of smooth projective schemes
  
  <fr:embedded-tex
hash="8951aea5b0a008d2dca1292914af55ed"><fr:embedded-tex-preamble>
     \usepackage {amsmath}
     \usepackage {amssymb}
     \usepackage {tikz-cd}
  </fr:embedded-tex-preamble><fr:embedded-tex-body>\begin {tikzcd} 
    X_ \bullet  =  \Big ( \ldots \quad 
    X_2
       \ar [r]
       \ar [r,shift left=4]
       \ar [r,shift right=4]
    &amp; X_1
       \ar [r,shift left=2]
       \ar [r,shift right=2]
       \ar [l,shift right=2]
       \ar [l,shift left=2]
    &amp; X_0 \Big )
       \ar [l]
   \end {tikzcd}</fr:embedded-tex-body></fr:embedded-tex>

  (or, as we will say, by a smooth projective simplicial scheme).
  The results of [hodge-theory-iii-5 <fr:strong>(?)</fr:strong>] and [hodge-theory-iii-6 <fr:strong>(?)</fr:strong>] allow us to find such simplicial schemes <fr:tex>X_ \bullet</fr:tex> that have, in a suitable sense, the same cohomology as <fr:tex>X</fr:tex>.
  We can then "express", via a spectral sequence, the cohomology of <fr:tex>X</fr:tex> in terms of the cohomology of the <fr:tex>X_n</fr:tex>.
  Following the general principles of <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-i"
href="hodge-theory-i.xml"
taxon="Hodge Theory"
number="I"></fr:ref>, we can then, on each <fr:tex>X_n</fr:tex>, use classical Hodge theory, and obtain an induced mixed Hodge structure on the cohomology of <fr:tex>X</fr:tex>.
</fr:p><fr:p>
